🚨 Pre-Flight Setup
Environment: A fresh RHEL 10 VM.

Hardware: Add TWO unformatted virtual disks (e.g., /dev/vdb at 10GB, and /dev/vdc at 5GB).

Network: Ensure the VM has an active internet connection to pull packages and container images.

Time Limit: 3 Hours (180 Minutes).

The Golden Rule: You must reboot at the end. If it doesn't survive a reboot, you score 0 for that objective.

📝 RHCSA RHEL 10 Mock Exam: "The Sovereign Transition"
Task 0: The Break-In

Reboot your system. Interrupt the boot process, break into the system, and change the root password to RHEL10-secure!.

Task 1: System Networking

Set the hostname to rhel10-node.sovereign.lan.

Configure your primary network interface statically with the IP 10.0.0.50/24 and a gateway of 10.0.0.1 (or use your local KVM subnet if you prefer). Ensure it connects automatically.

Task 2: User and Identity Management

Create a group named sysops.

Create a user david with the UID 3020.

Create a user sarah.

Make both david and sarah supplementary members of sysops.

Ensure sarah's account password expires exactly 90 days from today.

Task 3: Collaborative Security (SGID & ACLs)

Create a directory /opt/ops_data.

Change the group ownership to sysops.

Ensure all new files created here inherit the sysops group.

Ensure the owner and group have read, write, and execute permissions. Others should have absolutely no access.

Copy the file /etc/passwd to /opt/ops_data/passwd_backup.

Configure an ACL on /opt/ops_data/passwd_backup so the user sarah has read and write permissions, without changing the file's primary owner or group.

Task 4: Storage Engineering (LVM)

Create a Volume Group named vg_server on your 10GB disk, with a physical extent size of 16MB.

Create a Logical Volume named lv_metrics using exactly 100 extents.

Format the volume with the xfs filesystem.

Mount it persistently to /var/log/metrics using its UUID.

Task 5: Swap Allocation

Create a 1GB Swap partition on your 5GB disk.

Format it and ensure it mounts persistently across reboots.

Task 6: The Archive Automator

Locate all files under /usr/share/doc that are larger than 2MB.

Copy them to /root/large_docs.

Create a cron job for the root user that runs every Monday at 3:15 AM. The job must create a compressed tarball of /root/large_docs and save it to /var/log/metrics/doc_backup.tar.gz.

Task 7: Secure Web Hosting (SELinux & Firewalld)

Install the Apache web server (httpd).

Configure the server to listen on port 8181.

Create a file at /var/www/html/index.html containing the text "Welcome to RHEL 10".

Configure SELinux to allow the web server to bind to port 8181.

Configure the firewall to permanently allow incoming TCP traffic on port 8181.

Ensure the service starts automatically on boot.

Task 8: Autofs (On-Demand Storage)

Configure autofs so that accessing /shares/internal automatically mounts a local directory.

The mapping should mount the local directory /var/tmp to /shares/internal using the -bind option.

Task 9: Modern Containerization (Podman Quadlets) ⚠️ RHEL 10 Specific

Log in as the user sarah.

Pull the httpd:latest image from a public registry (like docker.io).

Create a rootless Podman Quadlet configuration to run this container.

Name the container sarah_web.

Map port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container.

Ensure the container starts automatically as a systemd service for the user sarah, and survives system reboots without requiring sarah to log in first (enable lingering).
